["key_step_1", "The net force on the dipole is given by $\vec{F}=2 q(\vec{\omega} \times \vec{r}) \times \vec{B}$, where $\vec{p}$ is the dipole moment. The time derivative of the dipole moment is $\frac{d \vec{p}}{d t}=\vec{\omega} \times \vec{p}$. Using Newton's second law, $2 m \frac{d \vec{v}}{d t}=\vec{F}=\frac{d \vec{p}}{d t} \times \vec{B}$. Integrating, we obtain a conserved quantity: $2 m \vec{v}-\vec{p} \times \vec{B}=\mathrm{const}$.
"key_step_2", If $\vec{p}$ reverses direction from $\vec{p}_{0}$ to $\vec{p}_{1}=-\vec{p}_{0}$, then the change in velocity is $\vec{v}_{1}=\vec{v}_{0}+\frac{\left(\vec{p}_{1}-\vec{p}_{0}\right) \times \vec{B}}{2 m}=-\frac{\vec{p}_{0} \times \vec{B}}{m}$.
"key_step_3", Since the magnetic field does no work, kinetic energy is conserved: $\frac{I}{2} \omega_{0}^{2}=\frac{I}{2} \omega_{1}^{2}+\frac{2 m}{2} v_{1}^{2}$, where $I=\frac{m d^2}{2}$ is the moment of inertia. To minimize $\omega_0$, we set $\omega_1 = 0$. Solving for the minimal angular velocity, we get $\omega_{\min }=v_{1} \sqrt{\frac{2 m}{I}}=\frac{p_{0} B}{m} \sqrt{\frac{4}{d^{2}}}=\frac{2 q B}{m}$.
